ally care if it=E2=80=99s a Bristol-based platform=E2=80=94it just wants to=
 have the biggest stars on their air. That=E2=80=99s a far cry from the inc=
eption of the =E2=80=98This Is SportsCenter=E2=80=99 marketing campaign, wh=
ich was designed to paint Bristol as the center of the sports universe.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94A former ESPNer

On Fox=E2=80=99s streaming strategy: =E2=80=9CMy team buys media (I don=E2=
=80=99t), but Fox seems to be betting that people will hang on to their bun=
dle because they have football. At what point does the NFL tell them to go =
fly a kite and take that package to Netflix? Because I=E2=80=99d rather my =
team buy that than a dying bundle deal.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A media executive

On a former Fox Sports exec=E2=80=99s email questioning the NWSL=E2=80=99s =
expansion strategy: =E2=80=9CEveryone thinks this is me! Stop
taking quotes from Patrick Crakes.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94Another former Fox Spor=
ts executive

[Ed. note: Still another former Fox Sports executive Patrick Crakes did not=
 send the original email signed by =E2=80=9CA former Fox Sports executive.=
=E2=80=9D]

On cord-cutting: =E2=80=9CLast year, I got rid of Comcast after 20-plus yea=
rs, and through multiple moves, to go with YouTube TV. There were two big i=
ssues that Comcast never dealt with: 1. Even when they were losing subs, th=
e price never went down, it only kept going up. Plus, Comcast charges for e=
verything: monthly fees for the cable box and an extra box; a modem.
2. Customer service was terrible. I paused YouTube TV over the summer on th=
e computer. I did the same thing with Comcast, and it took multiple 45-plus=
-minute calls to get it right. I=E2=80=99d talk to multiple people every ti=
me, and I rarely got my problem fixed on the first call. Comcast did always=
 offer more products for me to buy, though.
=E2=80=94A Varsity subscriber

Have a great weekend. See you Monday.
John

